The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Calcutta, Feb. 7: A meeting by the central chief labour commissioner will be convened on February 9 here to work on the steps for reopening jute mills in Bengal. However, the trade unions, which have struck work for an indefinite period, have rejected proposals offered by the Indian Jute Mills Association on the contentious issue of dearness allowance.                            
	 New Delhi, Feb. 7: The steel ministry has said that Coal India Ltd and NTPC can exit International Coal Ventures Ltd (ICVL) if they do not wish to scout and buy coal properties abroad. The ministry is considering restructuring ICVL  a special purpose vehicle formed by SAIL, NTPC, CIL, NMDC and RINL to acquire coal assets abroad.                             
	 New Delhi, Feb. 7: The government has said it is not considering to give the Serious Fraud Investigation Office (SFIO) the powers to trail money stashed abroad by corporates. The SFIO has for long been seeking powers to carry out investigations abroad.                             
	 New Delhi, Feb. 7: The Indian banking system, on many parameters, is much ahead of the BRIC nations and developed countries as it has maintained resilience and continues to provide growth opportunities even in the current economic situation, industry body Ficci has said.                             
	 Tokyo, Feb. 7: Toyota, reeling under car safety woes that have sullied its global reputation, will this week announce the recall of 300,000 of its flagship Prius hybrid because of brake flaws, The Yomiuri Shimbun said.                             
	 London, Feb. 7: Kraft Foods chief executive Irene Rosenfeld has said owning UK-based Cadbury will enable the American confectionery giant to expand its footprint into the developing market, including India.                             
	 New Delhi, Feb. 7: Leading economist Jeffrey Sachs said India should continue with high government spending to stimulate growth, despite concerns over the bloating fiscal deficit, but called for a sustainable funding model.                                                                                                                          
